The photocatalytic activity (PCA) of synthesized catalysts was assessed by estimating the degradation rate of a combination of two toxic dyes namely methylene blue (MB) and ciprofloxacin (CF) in aqueous solution. The stock solution of dyes was prepared in DIW (10 mg/1000 mL) and 10 mg of prepared catalyst (pristine TiO2, C3N4, 0:1, 0.1:1, 0.2:1, 0.3:1) was added to 50 mL stock solution. After homogeneous stirring, solution was placed in a sealed box under mercury (Hg) lamp (wavelength 400 to 700 nm and power 400 W) at ~ 15 cm distance to avoid overheating. After 20 min interval, 3 mL solution was separated to check concentration of dyes present in the solution by utilizing UV–Vis spectroscopy. The degradation efficiency was determined by the formula given as:1Degradationefficiency(%)=Co-CtCo×100\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\text{Degradation}}\,{\text{efficiency}}\,(\% ) = \frac{Co - Ct}{{Co}} \times 100$$\end{document}
where Co and Ct initial and final concentration of dye at time t = 0 and at final time t, respectively [22].

Free radical scavenging activity of all samples was examined using the method reported by Kibiti and Afolayan [23] with certain modifications. Various concentrations of pristine TiO2, C3N4, and C3N4 doped TiO2 nanoparticles (0–500 µg/mL) were prepared and mixed with equal volume of 0.1 mM DPPH solution. The reaction mixture was vortex and incubated for 30 min in dark at ambient temperature. Ascorbic acid was employed as a reference antioxidant. Absorbance of mixture was measured at 517 nm using spectrophotometer. The % scavenging ability was calculated using equation:DPPHscavengingrate%=A0-A1A0×100\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\text{DPPH}}\,{\text{scavenging}}\,{\text{rate}} \left( \% \right) = \frac{{\left( {A_{0} - A_{1} } \right)}}{{A_{0} }} \times 100$$\end{document}
where A0 is absorption of control (Methanol + DPPH) and A1 is absorbance of sample.

